document.getElementById('app').innerHTML = '<article class="live-article"><h1>Live Blog: Emergency Preparedness Drill</h1><p class="byline">By Alyssa Green | March 6, 2026</p><p>City agencies staged a coordinated emergency drill Tuesday morning to test how quickly transit operations, hospitals, and school districts can exchange verified updates. Observers said the exercise focused on message timing rather than dramatic simulation, with each department asked to publish short status notes every fifteen minutes.</p><p>At the operations center, dispatch teams used a shared incident board that automatically tagged updates by neighborhood and service type. Officials said that structure reduced duplicate alerts and helped call-center staff answer resident questions without switching between separate systems.</p><p>Transit supervisors reported that reroute notices reached station monitors within two minutes on average, while hospital liaisons confirmed bed-availability updates were posted on schedule throughout the drill window. Evaluators noted that multilingual templates improved readability for non-English audiences during the busiest phase.</p><p>The city manager\'s office plans to publish an after-action memo next week summarizing delays, communication gaps, and recommended process changes before hurricane season begins in June.</p></article>';